        " in Africa, ruled in theory by a Conseil de défense de lEmpire set up by De Gaulle on 27 October 1940. The FEA centred on Middle Congo went overnight from a backwater to a linchpin of Free French forces in Africa. Point Noire in particular became a vital transit area and base for bringing supplies, soldiers and labor from the interior to the coast and back again. The intense use of the railway led to the rise of a new urban labor class and improved the infrastructure of the colony.        In this revolt the then-governor of Chad ": null
    },
    {
        "Félix Eboué": "Félix Eboué"
    },
    {
        " played a key role. Because of this and his earlier support for De Gaulle he became Governor-General of the Afrique Equatoriale Française in 1940, the first non-white to achieve this position in French colonial history. Born in 1884 in ": null
    },
    {
        "French Guiana": "French Guiana"
    },
    {
